snippet.textDisplay: Aaj Rang Hai often called Rang or Rung (Persian for colour), is a Qawwali composed by Amir Khusro[1] in appreciation of Sufi saint Nizamuddin Auliya. It is a staple of most Qawwali sessions in North India and Pakistan, specially in the Chishti shrines of Delhi. Traditionally it is sung as a closing piece at the end of a Qawwali session.
snippet.textOriginal: Aaj Rang Hai often called Rang or Rung (Persian for colour), is a Qawwali composed by Amir Khusro[1] in appreciation of Sufi saint Nizamuddin Auliya. It is a staple of most Qawwali sessions in North India and Pakistan, specially in the Chishti shrines of Delhi. Traditionally it is sung as a closing piece at the end of a Qawwali session.

snippet.textDisplay:
“Rung” here refers to the Noor (light, splendour) and Faiz(grace) of Khwaja Nizamuddin Aulia. The Qawalli is written by Hazrat Amir Khusrau in his trademark Hindavi/Braj language.

The story in the song goes thus:-

When Khusrau came back from the dargah of Khwaja, he told his mother that the place was so unique that it almost took his breath away.

He has wandered the length and breadth of the country and even foreign lands, but has never been able to come across any place which could give him so much happiness and peace.
